caption: Right feel but the chocolate egg cream was not good. It is all about the syrup. If the syrup is not a high quality (it doesn't need to be Fox's Uber's, that's a myth perpetrated by Junior's) it will be weak and unable to correlate with the seltzer. The milk MUST be a whole milk and in the old days was unpasteurized. Ideally, to recreate this flavor, try using half and half. We have actually done research on this. In The Bronx egg creams are done with syrup added last making a brown foam. In Brooklyn, they do milk and syrup simultaneously making white foam. We genuinely think the other boroughs just do them wrong. We are from The Bronx of course. Enjoy!

Hidden gem in plain sight, there are so many places to eat around here, dozens of fast food chains. As a lover of the drinks we decided to give this place a chance, and it was a delightful surprise. The staff was so friendly, professional, and attentive to every customer. I had a bacon cheeseburger deluxe with onion rings (non-greasy.) My lady had a breakfast eggs and bacon (cooked to a crisp) just as she ordered and likes. I would highly recommend this place, as it has an old school diner look and feel, as well as run with cleanliness and professional manner with the customers first. Be warned we didn't try the desserts, but most will have a hard time avoiding them, especially if a root beer float is your thing, which I promised myself to tackle our next visit. If your in the area, avoid all the fast food chains, the price is very economical!!!

This location used to be Hinsch's, a classic Bay Ridge diner that closed down a few years ago after existing for decades.  I went there for ice cream with my family.  The ice cream tasted like homemade and was delicious.  It was served in one of those metal serving dishes.  Everything about this restaurant made me reminisce about the old days.  The place was lovingly restored with many details that the original diners had decades ago.  There were many large photos hanging along the walls showing how Bay Ridge looked long ago.  There was even an article on the wall describing the Stewart's Story.  This place is a welcome addition to Bay Ridge in an area that is overrun with modern-day food franchises.  This restaurant is equally good for those who want be served a full meal or are simply paying a visit to  enjoy their ice cream.  Once you walk away from the reality of what 5th Avenue has become today and into this establishment, you will be transported into another time period where the stress will just melt away as you reminisce about a more innocent time period.
